er of areas. They were crucial to foreign and domestic relations, and chivalric culture; and, of course, they were to become the powerbrokers of heraldic symbols and genealogy. However, despite the high levels at which they operated, their roles in these areas remain largely unexplored, with scholarship tending to focus on the science of heraldry rather than the heralds themselves. This collection aims to remedy that neglect. The contributions cover a range of European regions [particularly Florence, Scandinavia, Poland, the German Empire, the Burgundian Low Countries, Brittany, Scotland and England] and discuss the diverse roles and experiences of heralds in the late Middle Ages. Contributors: JACKSON W. ARMSTRONG, ADRIAN AILES, KATIE STEVENSON, MICHAEL JONES, FRANCK VILTART, HENRI SIMMONEAU, WIM VAN ANROOIJ, BOGDAN WOJCIECH BRZUSTOWICZ, ALEXIA GROSJEAN, LAURA CIRRI  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHeraldryzEuropexHistoryyTo 1500. 4aHeraldry & Genealogy. 4aMedieval History. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMiddle Ages.  achivalric culture.  aducal courts.  agenealogy.  aheraldic symbols.  akings of arms.  anoble families.  aofficers of arms.  aofficers of the crown.  apursuivants.1 aAiles, Adrian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnrooij, Wim van, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Jackson W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aArmstrong, Jackson Webster, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrzustowicz, Bogdan Wojciech, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCirri, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrosjean, Alexia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb